The container troubleshooting playbook.

There are seven container failure modes you will meet again and again, each with a clear first move. When a container will not start, you check its status, read its logs, and inspect its state for the exit code and the out-of-memory flag, and the usual culprits are a bad command, missing files, an immediate crash, or running out of memory. When it starts and then exits immediately, you read its logs, or you boot it with a shell as its command instead, or bypass its entry-point, to get a foothold to poke around from.

When it is running but the app inside is unhealthy, you get a shell inside it, list its processes, and check what it is actually listening on. When you cannot reach it from outside, you check what is published, try to reach it from the host, look at the firewall rules, and confirm the app is binding all interfaces rather than just loopback, which is the single most common cause, because loopback inside a container is reachable only from inside. When two containers cannot talk, you check which networks each is attached to and debug from a container on the network, remembering that containers on different user-defined networks cannot reach each other and that the default bridge gives no name resolution.

When a container is slow, you watch its live resource usage and check its configured limits, and if it is hitting a memory or see-pee-you cap you raise it. And when it dies with the kill-signal exit code, that almost always means it hit its memory limit or someone killed it, so you inspect its state for the out-of-memory flag and check the host's kernel messages for the out-of-memory event, then either raise the limit or fix whatever was consuming the memory. Run through these seven in order and you will diagnose the great majority of container problems quickly.
